04319nam a22007095i 9789048505289DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20042004ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485052897 a10.1515/97890485052892doi  a(DE-B1597)532932  a(OCoLC)55848895  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 4aHC305 7aPOL0000002bisacsh0481pa330qDE-1011 aFerrera, Maurizio, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRescued by Europe? :bSocial and Labour Market Reforms in Italy from Maastricht to Berlusconi /cElisabetta Gualmini, Maurizio Ferrera. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2004] 4cÂ©2004  a1 online resource (200 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aChanging Welfare States00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList Of Tables And Figures -- tIntroduction -- tI. Adjusting To Europe:A Learning Perspective -- tII. The Scene In The 1970S: Light,Shadow And Thunder -- tIII. The Winding Road To Adjustment -- tIV. The Cycle Of Reform -- tV. Reforms As Outcomes Of Institutional Learning -- tVI. Rescued,But Still Free To Harm Itself -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tList Of Abbreviations -- tIndex Of Names -- tIndex Of Subjects0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs a result of its political and economic turmoil for much of the postwar period, Italy was considered the "bad seed" in the European community. Harsh ideological divisions, chronic executive instability, inefficient bureaucracy, uneven socio-economic development, organized crime, and unbalanced public finances all contributed to this negative perception of the nation. Yet a massive economic and social overhaul was launched in the 1990s as part of Italy's efforts to meet the famous Maastricht requirements in order to join the Economic and Monetary Union (EMU). This book examines the processes Italy underwent to become part of the integrated European community and skillfully analyzes the consequences of the "Maastricht process" by exploring the effect it had on governmental and social actions and modes of orientation. Rescued by Europe? offers sharp insights into the importance of welfare state reform to current Berlusconi government, and how the weakening of the European Union's constraints has renewed the resistance to further changes. Ferrera and Gualmini ultimately argue that the constraints and opportunities linked to European integration have been the driving forces behind Italy's positive expansions, yet even with these reforms, there is still a long road ahead for European integration and Italy's political future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aLabor marketzItaly. 0aPublic welfarezItaly. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aGualmini, Elisabetta, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAUP eBook Package Backfile 2000-2013z978311070067140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978904850528940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048505289423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9789048505289.jpg  a978-3-11-070067-1  AUP eBook Package Backfile 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK